==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bauwa-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[buwa]] (Frisian [[bouwje]]), Old Saxon ''būan'' (Dutch [[bouwen]]), Old High German [[buwan|būwan]] (German [[bauen]] ‘build’), Old Norse [[búa]] (Icelandic [[búa]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐌿𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bu:an/

===Verb===
'''būan''' (class 1 weak)
# to [[live]] or [[dwell]]
#:''He bude on East-Englum'': he lived with the East Angles.  (''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'')
# to [[inhabit]], to [[occupy]]
#:''Ne mæg mon meduseld buan'': a man may not occupy the mead-bench,  (''Beowulf'')

